  "kurse": [
    {
      "id": 36268,
      "kuerzel": "IPCV2",
      "bezeichnung": "Image Processing and Computer Vision 2",
      "lernziele": "<p>At the end of the module the students are expected to understand the following concepts and be able to apply them to real world image processing and computer vision problems:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Classic object recognition</li>\n<li>Image Description</li>\n<li>Single and Multiple View Geometry</li>\n<li>Structure from Motion</li>\n<li>Neural Network Methods</li>\n<li>Further Topics</li>\n</ul>",
      "planinhalt": "<p>The module is structured as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Classic object recognition</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Image Description</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Single and Multiple View Geometry</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Structure from Motion</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Neural Network Methods</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Further Topics</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "bibliographie": "<p>The module is based on lecture slides, exercises and the books</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Richard Szeliski, Computer Vision: Algorithms and Applications, 2nd Edition, 2022, Springer: free download from https://szeliski.org/Book/ after registration</li>\n<li>\"Digital Image Processing, 4th ed.\" by Rafael C.Gonzalez and Richard E. Woods. There is a website dedicated to this book with useful information: http://www.imageprocessingplace.com/</li>\n</ul>",
